		<li id="comment-57494" class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 with-avatar">

			<div id="div-comment-57494" class="comment-body">
				
				<div class="comment-author-avatar"><img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/6c557173837e9593e6c632dd1fa9d10a?s=64&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fruhlman.com%2Fwp-includes%2Fimages%2Fblank.gif&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-64 photo' height='64' width='64' /><span class="avatar-overlay"></span></div>				<div class="comment-content">
					<div class="comment-meta">
						<cite class="fn"><a href='http://twitter.com/jenilowrance' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Jeni</a></cite>
						<span class="date">April 12, 2010 at 12:47 pm</span>
					</div>

					<div class="comment-text">
						<p>There&#8217;s a couple of other things I consider mandatory:</p>
<p>A set of locking tongs<br />
A couple of good spatulas (of both the flipping variety and the scraping/mixing variety)<br />
An oven thermometer (ah, apartment living)<br />
A bench scraper</p>
<p>But, of course, it&#8217;s my scale that&#8217;s my true workhorse. I have celiac and thus bake everything from scratch, and I couldn&#8217;t do it without a scale. </p>
<p>(As an aside, can I mention how amazing _Ratio_ is for gluten-free baking? Save bread dough, nearly every ratio translates perfectly from traditional flours to gluten-free flours. My family thinks I&#8217;m a genius.)</p>
					</div>

